        <section class="segment-opener" data-uuid="192ed0bd67a54ed7bd7d17f4f5c88543">
            <article data-uuid="e20fc60f2ab54dcb8502db0cdf4eb8e9">
                <h4 data-uuid="445b7ba0df014b1290a04f4e1e12cccd">Main Idea</h4>
                <p class="main-idea" data-uuid="3900737680f94facba3401ec0d6620ad">A new Constitution provided a framework for a stronger national government.</p>
                <h2 data-uuid="4916bc29f3b74c95b3c493bc343ef07a">The Constitution</h2>
                <div class="yellow-star-yellow-bar" data-uuid="1fd5d7e2b533442eb50895584645aea4"></div>
            </article>
        </section>
        <p data-uuid="a03f5a4a5f0349ada2453a96b65b3253">The system of government established by the Constitution is called federalism. Under <dfn title="federalism">federalism</dfn> powers are divided between the states and the federal, or national, government. States keep control over many issues, such as local government and local laws. The sharing of power between the national and state governments is one of the strengths of the Constitution.<br />
        </p>
        <h3 data-uuid="c653f3d821fa42899611962da5115d76">Separation of Powers</h3>
        <p data-uuid="50b45a705bb046978bf6e407a35a7a68">The power of the federal government is divided among three branches. The legislative branch, or Congress, passes laws. The executive branch, made up of the president and many departments, makes sure the laws are carried out. The judicial branch, consisting of the national courts, interprets laws and punishes criminals.</p>
